{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bc03f490-7ec9-41bc-8f0a-2786506b2474","content":"## What's happening\n\nStarting with **.NET 9**, Microsoft raised the minimum x86-64 CPU baseline on Linux from **x86-64-v1** (original amd64, SSE/SSE2 only) to **x86-64-v2**, which requires:\n\n- **SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2**\n- **POPCNT**\n- **CMPXCHG16B**\n\nYour 2012-era hardware likely has a CPU that lacks one or more of these (e.g., an older AMD Bulldozer variant, or a low-power Intel Atom). .NET 10 may have still tolerated it, but by .NET 11 the v2 baseline is strictly enforced.\n\n## How to confirm\n\nOn the failing node, run:\n\n```bash\ngrep -E 'sse4_2|popcnt|ssse3' /proc/cpuinfo\n```\n\nIf any of those are missing, the CPU doesn't meet x86-64-v2.\n\n## Your other targets are fine\n\n| Target | Why it's unaffected |\n|---|---|\n| **Windows Arm64** (Surface Pro X) | Arm64 has its own baseline; SQ1 meets it |\n| **Raspberry Pi 4** (Linux Arm64) | Same — Arm64 baseline, not x86 |\n| **Newer x86-64 Linux nodes** | Any Intel Nehalem+ (2008) or AMD Jaguar/Zen+ generally has v2 |\n\n## Options\n\n1. **Replace the hardware** — any x86-64 CPU from ~2013+ should have v2 support.\n2. **Stay on the last supported .NET version** for that node and migrate workloads off it.\n3. **Build a custom .NET runtime** from source targeting v1 (unsupported, not recommended for production).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"31a6f25f-40d3-42a2-be2f-7f4cda348f07","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's hardware requirements, so I can answer directly.\n\nStarting with .NET 9, Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline from the original x86-64 (v1) to x86-64-v2, which requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT. However, let me think more carefully about the timeline.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The user mentions .NET 10 to .NET 11. As of my knowledge:\n\n\nIn .NET 8, the x86-64 baseline was still the original x86-64 (SSE, SSE2).\nStarting with .NET 9, Microsoft began requiring x86-64-v2 on Linux, which needs SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT.\n\nBut wait—the user mentioned running .NET 10 fine and only hitting issues with .NET 11, which hasn't even been released yet (we're in May 2026, so .NET 11 would come around November 2026). The real problem is that hardware from 2012 likely doesn't support x86-64-v2 at all, which is why the upgrade broke things. -64-v2, which includes AVX, AVX2, BMI1, BMI2, F16C, FMA, LZCNT, MOVBE, and OSXSAVE. Hardware from 2012 wouldn't have all of these—AVX2 didn't arrive until Haswell in 2013. The error message about \"baseline instruction sets\" is exactly what .NET throws when the CPU falls short of minimum requirements, so this points to .NET 9 raising the bar to x86-64-v2, and the user either upgraded from .NET 8 or earlier, or .NET 10 might have been skipped. Older CPUs from that era likely lack some of these required instructions, so I'll base my answer on the documented .NET 9 change that raised the Linux x86-64 baseline to v2, which explains what the user is experiencing.","outputTokens":1693,"requestId":"884D:354872:1F78ACB:22EF94A:69FA9C8D"},"id":"2bace7f5-5d86-425c-be68-7e1115a44f2d","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:43:14.128Z","parentId":"9173c040-8a7c-4503-92f5-69b1772ad668"}
